{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486795"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"177"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/177"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.01,0.41,0.26,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"177"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49096"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/177"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-09-26T01:35:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-10T22:01:04+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-07-14T22:20:04+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-27 07:07:21"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"177"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16119"}},"author":{"data":null},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34137"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"460"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3311"},{"type":"tags","id":"3382"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15417"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42017"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44451"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34137"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49096"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with an eight-hour history of upper abdominal pain, associated with nausea and vomiting. The pain came on gradually and has now started to radiate through to his back. He has a history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. He has a pulse rate of 96/min, blood pressure 140/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.3\u00b0C. There is tenderness in the upper abdomen. His laboratory investigations are normal, apart from a serum lipase of 220 U/L (0-60).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors is most likely to have contributed to his current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recently starting an ACE inhibitor for hypertension","Family history of hyperparathyroidism","Gallstones noted incidentally on an ultrasound six years ago","Triglyceride level of 6.0 mmol/L (0.3-2.0)","Consumption of four standard drinks of alcohol the previous evening"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has acute pancreatitis, as evidenced by his clinical presentation and elevated serum lipase. The two most common causes of acute pancreatitis are \u003Cstrong\u003Egallstones\u003C/strong\u003E and alcohol. Gallstones are the most common cause of acute pancreatitis, being responsible for at least 40% of cases. Chronic alcohol consumption is the next most common cause, accounting for about 35% of cases. This patient has known gallstones, and even though he might have consumed a few drinks the evening before his presentation, it is the documented gallstones that would have been the likely trigger for this episode of acute pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Econsumption of four standard drinks\u003C/strong\u003E the previous evening, while not ideal, is unlikely to be the primary cause of acute pancreatitis in this case. Alcohol-induced pancreatitis is typically associated with chronic, heavy alcohol use rather than occasional moderate consumption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe third most common cause of acute pancreatitis is iatrogenic (post ERCP or cardiopulmonary bypass), accounting for about 20% of all cases. Other recognised causes (e.g., \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypertriglyceridaemia\u003C/strong\u003E, hypercalcaemia) collectively account for less than 5% of cases. While some drugs can be associated with acute pancreatitis, \u003Cstrong\u003EACE inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E are not commonly implicated. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efamily history of hyperparathyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E is not directly related to the patient\u0027s current condition. While hyperparathyroidism can cause hypercalcemia, which is a rare cause of pancreatitis, a family history alone would not be sufficient to trigger an acute episode.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gallstones are the most common cause of acute pancreatitis.","Serum lipase elevation is a key diagnostic feature of acute pancreatitis."],"references":["Forsmark CE, Vege SS, Wilcox CM. Acute Pancreatitis. N Engl J Med 2016;375:1972-81. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27959604/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34137"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"177"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions"